    2.1 Research we can trust

    We want our research findings to be trustworthy ‚Äì meaning that at the very least, other researchers should be able get the same results when running the same experiments and analyzing the data in the same way (meaning that our results are replicable).

    But: Collecting new data can be costly in terms of time and resources (esp.¬†for EEG and fMRI studies). Still, simply sharing one‚Äôs existing data allows others to establish the reproducibility of the results (a prerequisite for replicability) as well as their robustness (a prerequisite for generalizatbility).

    2.2 Why open data?

    Pros and cons of open data
    Pros Cons

    • Others can try to reproduce your analysis

    • Others can probe the robustness of your results (e.g., use different exclusion criteria or software packages)

    • Others can analyze their own research questions

    • Others can use your data for methods development and teaching

    • You have a (well-documented) backup of the data

    • You will get cited when others use your data

    • Increased return for participants‚Äô time and taxpayers‚Äô money

    • Privacy concerns -> Informed consent, pseudonymization

    • Additional effort in preparing and documenting the data

    • Fear of getting ‚Äúscooped‚Äù

    2.5 The ERP CORE data

    2.6 Downloading ERP CORE data

    The ERP CORE data can be downloaded directly from the OSF website (https://osf.io/thsqg/). But we‚Äôre instead going to use the R package erpcore.

    But first, let‚Äôs create an empty directory for storing the data. Again, we could do this manually, or we could use R. The here() function from the here package makes it possible to define the directory with a relative path. This is useful because it means that the code will work regardless of from where in the file system we‚Äôre running it.

    data_dir <- here::here("data/n170")
data_dir
    ## [1] "/home/runner/work/eegSeminaR/eegSeminaR/data/n170"
    dir.create(data_dir, recursive = TRUE)

    Now we can use the get_erpcore() function to download the data into this directory. We choose the "bids" version of the data (there also is a "raw" version on OSF that has the data before they were converted to BIDS).

    For the examples in class we only need the data from the N170 task and from one subject (here "sub-001"). For your group projects focussing on one of the other ERP tasks/components, you may want to download the full data from all subjects (by leaving the subjects argument blank).

    erpcore::get_erpcore(
  component = "n170",
  dest_path = data_dir,
  type = "bids",
  subjects = "sub-001"
)
